{
  "result": "At dawn, the city seemed less like a machine and more like a thought still deciding what to become. Windows caught a pale wash of gold; pigeons negotiated rooflines; a baker lifted the first tray of bread from an oven and filled the street with proof that warmth can be made deliberately.\n\nI like that hour because nothing has hardened yet. Plans are soft. Regrets have not found their full vocabulary. Even traffic lights blink with unusual patience, as if admitting that rules are only useful when they help people meet safely in the middle.\n\nA stray dog trotted past a newspaper kiosk, tail held high, carrying no headlines, no appointments, no theories about the future. It knew the important things: where rain collects, which hands are kind, how to sleep in a square of sun. Watching it, I envied the elegance of attention without ambition.\n\nSoon the day would gather speed. Phones would bloom with demands. Someone would argue over money, someone would fall in love, someone would forget to call home. The ordinary orchestra would begin tuning itself in honks, shoes, keyboards, kettles, doors.\n\nBut for a few minutes, everything rested on the edge of happening. The world was not innocent, exactly; it was simply unfinished. That felt like enough. Not a promise, not forgiveness, not a revelation with trumpets, just space. I stood there breathing bread and petrol and wet stone, grateful that beginnings can arrive quietly, asking nothing except that we notice before moving on again.",
